Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Pour the @water for the rice{300%ml} into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting
#lid{}. Stir in the @Basmati Rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the
boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still
covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to
serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

While the rice cooks, halve, peel and thinly slice the @Echalion Shallot{1/2}.

Halve the @Red Chilli{1/2}, lengthways, deseed, then finely chop. Peel and grate
the @Garlic Clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Pop the @Sea Bass Fillets{2} into a #medium bowl{} with the @Olive Oil for the
Marinade{3/4%tbsp} and @Curry Powder Mix{1%sachet}. Season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}, then mix well.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw fish.

Heat a drizzle of @?olive oil{} in a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the shallot, then season with @salt{}, @pepper{} and stir in the
@sugar{1%tsp}. Fry, stirring occasionally, until soft and sweet, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Meanwhile, lay the sea bass onto a #baking tray{} lined with #baking paper{},
skin-side down. Once the shallot has caramelised for ~{5%minutes}, bake the fish
on the top shelf until cooked through, ~{10-15%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The fish is cooked when opaque in the middle.

Once the shallot is caramelised, lower the heat and add the garlic,
@Tomato Puree{30%g} and @Tikka Masala Paste{75%g}. Fry for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @Creme Fraiche{75%g} and @Water for the Sauce{200%ml}, then simmer
until thickened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Once thickened, add the @Baby Spinach{40%g} a handful at a time until wilted and
piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}. Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed,
then remove from the heat. Add a splash of water if it's a little too thick.

When everything's ready, fluff up the rice work a #fork{}, then spoon into
#bowls{}.

Spoon over the curry sauce and top with the sea bass. Finish with a sprinkle of
chilli over the top (add less if you'd prefer things milder). Enjoy!